[This bug has been mentioned before](https://github.com/aspnet/Home/issues/2024), but it was not addressed.

#### Issue description

In a Web API ASP.NET Core project, upon POST, model binding starts to occur and the JsonConverters are hit, but during the binding a stack overflow exception occurs before it enters the controller action.

#### Steps to reproduce the issue

1. Create a ASP.NET Core Web API project targetting the `netcoreapp2.0` framework and referencing the [`System.DirectoryServices` NuGet package](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.DirectoryServices/).

2. Create a basic `User` model with a property of type [`System.Security.Principal.SecurityIdentifier`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.DirectoryServices/) (the official type for an Active Directory account SID). Nest that `User` model inside a `ComplexModel`. Example:

```csharp
public class User
{	
	[JsonConverter(typeof(SecurityIdentifierJsonConverter))]
	public SecurityIdentifier ObjectSid { get; set; }
}

public class ComplexModel
{	
	public User User { get; set; }
}
```

3.  Create an `[HttpPost]` action with `[FromBody] ComplexModel model` as the parameter. Example:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
[Authorize]
[ValidateAntiForgeryToken]
[Route("create")]
public async Task<IActionResult> Create([FromBody] ComplexObject complexObject)
{
	return Ok();
}
```

4. Load a JsonConverter to properly convert the `SecurityIdentifier` as it comes in. The one I used is below:
```csharp
public class SecurityIdentifierJsonConverter : JsonConverter
{
	public override void WriteJson(JsonWriter writer, object value, JsonSerializer serializer)
	{
		var sid = (SecurityIdentifier) value;
		serializer.Serialize(writer, sid != null ? sid.Value : value);
	}
	
	public override object ReadJson(JsonReader reader, Type objectType, object existingValue, JsonSerializer serializer)
	{
		var readerValue = reader.Value?.ToString();
		SecurityIdentifier sid = null;
		if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(readerValue))
		{
			sid = new SecurityIdentifier(readerValue);
		}
		return sid ?? new JsonSerializer().Deserialize(reader, objectType);
	}

	public override bool CanConvert(Type objectType) => objectType == typeof(SecurityIdentifier);
}
```
5. Attempt to POST.

#### What's the expected result?

The model minds without issue and the controller action executes.

#### What's the actual result?

```csharp
System.InsufficientExecutionStackException: Insufficient stack to continue executing the program safely. This can happen from having too many functions on the call stack or function on the stack using too much stack space.
   at System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RuntimeHelpers.EnsureSufficientExecutionStack()
   at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ModelBinding.Validation.ValidationVisitor.Visit(ModelMetadata metadata, String key, Object model)
   at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ModelBinding.Validation.ValidationVisitor.VisitChildren(IValidationStrategy strategy)
   at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ModelBinding.Validation.ValidationVisitor.VisitComplexType(IValidationStrategy defaultStrategy)
   at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ModelBinding.Validation.ValidationVisitor.Visit(ModelMetadata metadata, String key, Object model)
   at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ModelBinding.Validation.ValidationVisitor.VisitChildren(IValidationStrategy strategy)
   at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ModelBinding.Validation.ValidationVisitor.VisitComplexType(IValidationStrategy defaultStrategy)
   ...
```

The last 3 lines of the stacktrace repeat thousands of times.

#### Additional details / screenshot

Changing the SID property from type `System.Security.Principal.SecurityIdentifier` to `System.String` in the bound object stops the exception and essentially fixes the problem, but this is still a serious bug and happens when binding other objects as well (see #2024).

